<author><name><![CDATA[lidnariq]]></name></author>
<updated>2014-07-07T16:37:52-07:00</updated>
<published>2014-07-07T16:37:52-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=11401&amp;p=130776#p130776</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=11401&amp;p=130776#p130776"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Need help getting famicom p2 mic to work on U.S. toaster]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=11401&amp;p=130776#p130776"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle">Memblers wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />Also, I believe the coin input of the VS Dual/Unisystem uses the same input as the FC mic.  With the right kind of ROM hack (to fix the palette), maybe you could yell into the mic to insert a coin, heheh.<br /></div>Service button, not coin drop, but for many games it's equivalent.<br /><br />Anyway, let's take a step back: How do you (the panda of nom) know that the microphone works? What test tools do you have? (multimeter, oscilloscope, audio amplifier, flash cartridge)<br /><br />Here's some simple things you could try:<br /><br /><a href="http://www43.tok2.com/home/cmpslv/Famic/Famic.htm" class="postlink">Reference schematics courtesy enri</a>.<br />Scroll down to <strong>コントローラ、その他</strong> for controllers and <strong>Ｉ/Ｏポート周り</strong> for the interface logic inside the famicom.<br /><br />If you use an amplifier, consider using headphones, or else be careful about feedback.<br /><br />Open the controller, plug the microphone-containing into power, put an oscilloscope or audio amplifier on the microphone. (One side should be ground, the other should contain the signal). Can you see/hear audio from that pin? If not, something's wrong immediately around the microphone.<br />If you can, do you see/hear audio on the output of the amplifier inside the controller? (pin 2 of the 4069 inside) If not, something's wrong with the amplifier.<br />Next, test the input side of the pertinent 74'368 on the NES mainboard (This should be pin 10 of U7). If not, something else is wrong; maybe one of the diode arrays.<br />Finally, see if you can toggle the readback of that pin: short that same pin 10 to ground.<br /><br />There are some differences between &quot;just connecting the controller to $4016.2&quot; and what the famicom does, but I'm not yet clear that matters. (Namely: NES has a 10kΩ pullup on its input; Famicom has 10kΩ/100nF lowpass)<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=3512">lidnariq</a> — Mon Jul 07, 2014 4:37 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
