<author><name><![CDATA[Memblers]]></name></author>
<updated>2014-07-07T14:38:07-07:00</updated>
<published>2014-07-07T14:38:07-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=11401&amp;p=130769#p130769</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=11401&amp;p=130769#p130769"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Need help getting famicom p2 mic to work on U.S. toaster]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=11401&amp;p=130769#p130769"><![CDATA[
You can see how the mic is hooked up on the Famicom schematic here (look under P5 on the upper left):<br /><a href="http://nesdev.com/Ntd_8bit.jpg" class="postlink">http://nesdev.com/Ntd_8bit.jpg</a><br /><br />Looks like it goes through a 10k resistor, with a 0.1uF cap to ground after, before going into the 40H368 buffer where it's read at D2 @ $4017.  And unlike all the other inputs to the buffers, there is no pull-up resistor on it.  Also you see where the signal splits at the beginning, the other part is getting mixed with the NES audio through a 10k resistor.  If it's hooked up like that, it should work.<br /><br />Also, I believe the coin input of the VS Dual/Unisystem uses the same input as the FC mic.  With the right kind of ROM hack (to fix the palette), maybe you could yell into the mic to insert a coin, heheh.<br /><br />BTW, there is one of Nintendo's test ROMs, at the end where it tests the controller, it also will detect the mic.  The one listed on top here: <a href="http://my.ais.net/~xtreme/SF/NES/Test_Carts/index.html" class="postlink">http://my.ais.net/~xtreme/SF/NES/Test_Carts/index.html</a><p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=10">Memblers</a> — Mon Jul 07, 2014 2:38 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
